data.summary: [at Barrons.com] - If you’re a semiconductor investor worried about the recent spate of rumors of order cuts by Apple (AAPL) for its iPhone production, don’t worry, writes Pacific Crest’s John Vinh, reiterating today his positive stance on suppliers such as Broadcom (AVGO), Analog Devices (ADI), and InvenSense (INVN). Vinh’s colleague, Andy Hargreaves, this morning issued a note in which he cut his estimates for how many iPhone’s Apple may sell this quarter, and next, and in all of fiscal 2017, citing the company having made some adjustments to what it asks suppliers to build for it. Drawing from that research, Vinh writes, "we believe iPhone 7 momentum has begun to slow,” but he’s not concerned about the chip companies: Despite a more-muted iPhone 7 outlook, we see limited risk to estimates given (1) positive results from our carrier surveys indicate more-aggressive inventory management, (2) component suppliers have taken a more conservative stance on iPhone 7, (3) current orders are consistent with pre-launch expectations.
